---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE, SITE_DESCRIPTION } from '../consts';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead title={SITE_TITLE} description={SITE_DESCRIPTION} />
	</head>
	<body>
		<Header />
		<main>
			<h1>Data Journal</h1>
			<p class="lead">
				A practical reference for anyone learning to <strong>pull, clean, and organize data</strong>.
				Whether you're working with APIs, databases, spreadsheets, or raw files — this journal
				covers the patterns and tools you need.
			</p>

			<hr />

			<h2>Start Here</h2>
			<p>
				New to working with data? Start with the fundamentals before diving into tools and code.
				These articles build on each other, so reading in order will give you the clearest path.
			</p>

			<ol class="guide-list">
				<li>
					<a href="/blog/getting-started-with-data">Getting Started with Data Collection</a>
					— Understand data sources, formats, and the basic collection workflow.
				</li>
				<li>
					<a href="/blog/working-with-csv-and-json">Working with CSV and JSON</a>
					— The two most common data formats and how to read, write, and convert them.
				</li>
				<li>
					<a href="/blog/pulling-data-from-apis">Pulling Data from REST APIs</a>
					— Use HTTP requests to fetch structured data from any public or private API.
				</li>
				<li>
					<a href="/blog/organizing-data-with-sql">Organizing Data with SQL</a>
					— Filter, sort, join, and aggregate data using standard SQL queries.
				</li>
				<li>
					<a href="/blog/python-pandas-data-wrangling">Python &amp; Pandas for Data Wrangling</a>
					— Load messy data into a DataFrame and reshape it into something usable.
				</li>
				<li>
					<a href="/blog/building-your-first-data-pipeline">Building Your First Data Pipeline</a>
					— Combine everything into a repeatable end-to-end workflow.
				</li>
			</ol>

			<hr />

			<h2>Why a Data Journal?</h2>
			<p>
				Most data tutorials jump straight to machine learning or dashboards without covering the
				unglamorous middle work: finding a data source, figuring out the right API endpoint,
				handling pagination, dealing with missing values, and getting everything into a consistent
				shape before you can analyze it.
			</p>
			<p>
				This journal focuses on exactly that middle work — the part that takes up 80% of real
				data projects. Every article is written to be copy-paste practical, with real code
				examples and explanations of <em>why</em> each step matters.
			</p>

			<hr />

			<h2>Topics Covered</h2>
			<ul class="topic-grid">
				<li><strong>Data Sources</strong> — APIs, databases, files, web scraping</li>
				<li><strong>Formats</strong> — CSV, JSON, Parquet, XML, spreadsheets</li>
				<li><strong>Tools</strong> — Python, SQL, curl, jq, pandas</li>
				<li><strong>Patterns</strong> — Pagination, authentication, rate limiting</li>
				<li><strong>Cleaning</strong> — Missing values, type coercion, deduplication</li>
				<li><strong>Organizing</strong> — Schemas, normalization, folder structures</li>
			</ul>

			<p>
				Browse all articles in the <a href="/blog">Articles</a> section, or read more
				<a href="/about">about this journal</a>.
			</p>
		</main>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>
<style>
	.lead {
		font-size: 1.1em;
		color: rgb(var(--gray-dark));
	}
	.guide-list {
		line-height: 2.2;
	}
	.guide-list a {
		font-weight: 700;
	}
	.topic-grid {
		columns: 2;
		column-gap: 2em;
	}
	@media (max-width: 720px) {
		.topic-grid {
			columns: 1;
		}
	}
	hr {
		margin: 2em 0;
	}
</style>
